<HEADLINE>
<P>
HARBOR DISTRICT BOARD BRISTLES AT IDEA OF TRIMMING BOUNDARIES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By SHANNA GOWENLOCK, Times Staff Writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Oxnard Harbor District, which governs the Port of Hueneme, bristled this 
week at a suggestion by the mayors of Oxnard and Port Hueneme that the 
district's boundaries be reduced, stripping some county residents of the right 
to elect port commissioners. 
</P>
<P>
District president Ray Fletcher said he does not want city officials in Oxnard 
and Port Hueneme to "mess up a good thing" by attempting to shrink the district 
to the size of those two cities. Such a move, he said, would affect the 
composition of the present five-member board of commissioners. 
</P>
<P>
"What we have has worked well so far, and we have brought the harbor to 
success," said Fletcher, an Oxnard resident. He said he fears losing a pool of 
qualified port commissioner candidates who live outside Oxnard and Port 
Hueneme. 
</P>
<P>
The district now spans those cities as well as Camarillo and parts of Thousand 
Oaks. 
</P>
<P>
Oxnard Mayor Nao Takasugi said the port commissioners have jumped the gun with 
their vociferous opposition, which surfaced at a district meeting this week, 
because neither city officially has moved to study the issue. 
</P>
<P>
"No action of any definitive nature has taken place yet," Takasugi said. "It 
may develop, but at this moment it's just conjectural, 
let's-suppose-this-happened speculation." 
</P>
<P>
Takasugi said he believes that the harbor district's boundaries are outdated 
because Oxnard and Port Hueneme bear the brunt of the industrial port's 
activity without what he called 'adequate represention" on its board. 
</P>
<P>
At present, only one commissioner, Fletcher, is from Oxnard. Three are from 
Camarillo, one is from Thousand Oaks, and none are from Port Hueneme. 
</P>
<P>
"There's no real impact of the port on other cities except Port Hueneme and 
Oxnard. So that's why I guess there's been some speculation on our part that 
perhaps a study should be done, or perhaps we should reduce the size of the 
district," he said. Altering the district would require the approval of the 
county's Local Agency Formation Commission. 
</P>
</TEXT>
